---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';
import '../../styles/course.css';
import LessonPage from '../../components/course/LessonPage';
import GatePanel from '../../components/assessment/GatePanel';
import TokenizerExplorer from '../../components/interactive/TokenizerExplorer';
---

<BaseLayout title="What Is a Token?">
  <LessonPage lessonId="L02" client:load>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Question</div>
      <div class="lesson-question">What is a token?</div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Intuition</div>
      <p>
        The model does not see characters or words. It sees <strong>tokens</strong> — pieces of text that come from a fixed vocabulary.
      </p>
      <p>
        A token might be a whole word, a word fragment, a punctuation mark, or even a single character.
        The tokenizer decides how to split input text into these pieces, and different tokenizers make different choices.
      </p>
      <p>
        The critical insight: <strong>token count and word count are not the same.</strong>
        "tokenization" might be one word but two or three tokens.
        A single space character might be its own token.
      </p>
      <p>
        When people say a model has a "context length of 128K tokens," they mean 128,000 of these pieces — not 128,000 words.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Interactive — Tokenizer Explorer</div>
      <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
        Type text below and see how it splits into tokens. Notice how token boundaries don't always match word boundaries.
      </p>
      <TokenizerExplorer client:load />
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Toy Example</div>
      <div class="toy-example">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
          The sentence "The cat sat on the mat." tokenizes as:
        </p>
        <div style="display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 6px; font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
          <span style="background: var(--surface-3); padding: 2px 8px; border-radius: 3px; border-bottom: 2px solid var(--sem-token);">The</span>
          <span style="background: var(--surface-3); padding: 2px 8px; border-radius: 3px; border-bottom: 2px solid var(--sem-attention);">·cat</span>
          <span style="background: var(--surface-3); padding: 2px 8px; border-radius: 3px; border-bottom: 2px solid var(--sem-ffn);">·sat</span>
          <span style="background: var(--surface-3); padding: 2px 8px; border-radius: 3px; border-bottom: 2px solid var(--sem-logits);">·on</span>
          <span style="background: var(--surface-3); padding: 2px 8px; border-radius: 3px; border-bottom: 2px solid var(--sem-kvcache);">·the</span>
          <span style="background: var(--surface-3); padding: 2px 8px; border-radius: 3px; border-bottom: 2px solid var(--sem-router);">·mat</span>
          <span style="background: var(--surface-3); padding: 2px 8px; border-radius: 3px; border-bottom: 2px solid var(--sem-expert);">.</span>
        </div>
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary);">
          6 words, 7 tokens. The <code>·</code> represents a leading space — it is part of the token, not separate.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Shapes</div>
      <div class="shape-card">
        <div>Input text: a string of characters</div>
        <div>After tokenization: a sequence of token pieces</div>
        <div>Sequence length (n_tokens): the number of tokens in the sequence</div>
        <div style="color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-2);">n_tokens ≠ n_words (usually n_tokens > n_words)</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Math</div>
      <p>
        The only math concept here is a <strong>discrete sequence</strong>.
        A tokenized input is an ordered list of symbols from a finite set:
      </p>
      <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--sem-token); background: var(--surface-3); padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); border-radius: var(--radius-sm); margin: var(--space-3) 0; display: inline-block;">
        tokens = [t&#x2081;, t&#x2082;, ..., t&#x2099;]
      </div>
      <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary);">
        where each t&#x1D62; is a symbol from the vocabulary.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Implementation Hook</div>
      <div class="impl-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          Real tokenizers use trained rules to decide how to split text — BPE uses learned merge operations, while other methods like unigram model a different objective.
          In <code>llama.cpp</code>, tokenization is handled before the model graph runs.
          The model never sees raw text — only integer token IDs.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Performance Hook</div>
      <div class="perf-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          Tokenization is fast relative to model computation. But the token count determines how much work the model must do.
          More tokens means more computation in every layer. This is why "context length" is measured in tokens — it directly controls the cost.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Check Yourself</div>
      <GatePanel
        client:load
        lessonId="L02"
        gateStrength="soft"
        questions={[
          {
            id: 'L02-q1',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'Why can one sentence produce more tokens than words?',
            tag: 'conceptual',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: 'Because the tokenizer always adds extra tokens', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'b', text: 'Because some words are split into multiple token pieces, and spaces/punctuation can be separate tokens', isCorrect: true },
              { id: 'c', text: 'Because tokens include hidden control characters', isCorrect: false },
            ],
            explanation: 'The tokenizer splits text into pieces from its vocabulary. Long or rare words may become multiple tokens. Spaces are often part of a token piece.',
          },
          {
            id: 'L02-q2',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'Why is context length measured in tokens, not words?',
            tag: 'shape',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: 'Because words are easier to count', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'b', text: 'Because the model operates on tokens — they are the actual unit of input and computation', isCorrect: true },
              { id: 'c', text: 'Because tokens are always shorter than words', isCorrect: false },
            ],
            explanation: 'The model sees tokens, not words. Every layer processes n_tokens positions. Context length in tokens is the true capacity budget.',
          },
        ]}
      />
    </div>

  </LessonPage>
</BaseLayout>
